110
00:05:31,519 --> 00:05:33,552
This is gonna be
the best Christmas ever.

111
00:05:33,554 --> 00:05:35,271
Yeah, swell.

112
00:05:35,273 --> 00:05:36,922
I got a great
new girlfriend.

113
00:05:36,924 --> 00:05:40,443
My girlfriend's got a
great new boyfriend.

114
00:05:40,445 --> 00:05:42,378
My mom is coming.

115
00:05:42,380 --> 00:05:45,564
So is mine.

116
00:05:47,417 --> 00:05:50,569
Wherever she is.

117
00:05:50,571 --> 00:05:51,787
Went to the Apple Store

118
00:05:51,789 --> 00:05:53,990
and bought myself
a bunch of cool presents.

119
00:05:53,992 --> 00:05:57,410
I went to the grocery store
and got myself an apple.

120
00:05:59,129 --> 00:06:02,331
Sounds like somebody's got
the holiday blues.

121
00:06:02,333 --> 00:06:03,499
Oh, little bit.

122
00:06:03,501 --> 00:06:05,334
My son's with his
mother and her husband,

123
00:06:05,336 --> 00:06:07,586
and this is my first Christmas
without Charlie.

124
00:06:07,588 --> 00:06:09,255
What would you two
normally do?

125
00:06:09,257 --> 00:06:11,257
Oh, we had kind of
a holiday tradition.

126
00:06:11,259 --> 00:06:13,792
Um, he would drink
a gallon of eggnog

127
00:06:13,794 --> 00:06:16,628
and then try to throw me
out of the house at gunpoint.

128
00:06:16,630 --> 00:06:18,814
Good times.

129
00:06:19,916 --> 00:06:22,151
Well, you're not going
to spend this year alone.

130
00:06:22,153 --> 00:06:24,770
You're going to have Christmas
with me and my mom.

131
00:06:24,772 --> 00:06:26,655
Well, thank you,
that's very nice of you.

132
00:06:26,657 --> 00:06:28,274
You want to hear a funny idea?

133
00:06:28,276 --> 00:06:29,942
You and my mom
are about the same age.

134
00:06:29,944 --> 00:06:32,028
If you guys started dating
and got married,

135
00:06:32,030 --> 00:06:33,996
you'd be my new daddy.

136
00:06:33,998 --> 00:06:37,083
Wait, h-hold on,
I-I'm your mom's age?

137
00:06:37,085 --> 00:06:38,667
How old do you think I am?

138
00:06:38,669 --> 00:06:41,120
I don't know, what, like 60?

139
00:06:41,122 --> 00:06:43,706
I'm 44.

140
00:06:43,708 --> 00:06:45,624
Oh, well, you look older.

141
00:06:47,628 --> 00:06:49,578
Oh, there she is.

142
00:06:49,580 --> 00:06:50,596
That's it.

143
00:06:50,598 --> 00:06:53,049
Tomorrow I start moisturizing.

144
00:06:54,101 --> 00:06:56,668
- Mom.
- Baby.

145
00:06:57,687 --> 00:06:59,271
Eyeball, eyeball.

146
00:06:59,273 --> 00:07:00,890
Nose and mouth.

147
00:07:00,892 --> 00:07:01,941
I love you north.

148
00:07:01,943 --> 00:07:02,892
I love you south.

149
00:07:05,179 --> 00:07:07,179
Hey, Alan, meet
my mother Robin.

150
00:07:07,181 --> 00:07:08,481
Nice to meet you, Alan.

151
00:07:08,483 --> 00:07:09,615
Likewise.

152
00:07:09,617 --> 00:07:11,283
Mom, let me show
you my place.

153
00:07:11,285 --> 00:07:14,036
Check it out, I
got my own ocean.

154
00:07:14,038 --> 00:07:15,621
Well, it's not
completely mine.

155
00:07:15,623 --> 00:07:17,656
I have to share the
other side with Japan.

156
00:07:17,658 --> 00:07:19,241
It's very nice, dear.

157
00:07:19,243 --> 00:07:21,577
Yeah, I'm rich.

158
00:07:21,579 --> 00:07:25,864
Well... I know
what I want for Christmas.

159
00:07:26,666 --> 00:07:29,301
♪ Men. ♪

160
00:07:29,303 --> 00:07:32,004
So how long have you two
been living together?

161
00:07:32,006 --> 00:07:34,223
A couple
of months.

162
00:07:34,225 --> 00:07:36,842
I see.

163
00:07:36,844 --> 00:07:38,761
I'm sorry, I-I have to ask.

164
00:07:38,763 --> 00:07:41,130
Is this the woman
you don't want me to meet?

165
00:07:42,833 --> 00:07:44,683
What?

166
00:07:44,685 --> 00:07:45,717
No.

167
00:07:45,719 --> 00:07:47,103
No, Alan is just a friend.

168
00:07:47,105 --> 00:07:48,320
Tell her.

169
00:07:48,322 --> 00:07:51,390
Butch and Sundance,
not Brokeback Mountain.

170
00:07:51,392 --> 00:07:53,058
Okay, sorry.

171
00:07:53,060 --> 00:07:55,361
I-I mean, you have to admit,
it's a rather strange set-up—

172
00:07:55,363 --> 00:07:58,864
a 33-year-old man living
with a 60-year-old.

173
00:08:00,233 --> 00:08:02,234
I'm 44.

174
00:08:02,236 --> 00:08:04,236
Right, me, too.

175
00:08:05,839 --> 00:08:07,506
Alan helped me through
my break-up with Bridget,

176
00:08:07,508 --> 00:08:08,841
and then he needed
a place to stay,

177
00:08:08,843 --> 00:08:10,909
so I asked him
to stick around.

178
00:08:10,911 --> 00:08:12,911
Oh, that is so like you.

179
00:08:13,931 --> 00:08:15,714
When Walden was
a little boy,

180
00:08:15,716 --> 00:08:19,385
he used to bring home sick,
helpless animals all the time.

181
00:08:21,188 --> 00:08:24,690
God help me,
I can't take that as an insult.

182
00:08:24,692 --> 00:08:26,758
So, uh, what do you do, Robin?

183
00:08:26,760 --> 00:08:27,693
I'm a primatologist.

184
00:08:27,695 --> 00:08:29,595
I, I work mainly
with gorillas.

185
00:08:29,597 --> 00:08:33,399
Oh, oh, so I guess that makes
you the gorilla my dreams.

186
00:08:37,070 --> 00:08:39,238
It was hysterical
when Bugs Bunny did it.

187
00:08:40,040 --> 00:08:42,158
And thanks
to the financial support

188
00:08:42,160 --> 00:08:43,542
of my brilliant son,
I have a private

189
00:08:43,544 --> 00:08:45,244
gorilla sanctuary in Temecula.

190
00:08:45,246 --> 00:08:45,995
Oh, no kidding?

191
00:08:45,997 --> 00:08:47,129
Yeah, we take
gorillas

192
00:08:47,131 --> 00:08:48,297
who were born
in captivity

193
00:08:48,299 --> 00:08:50,049
and those who have lost
their wild habitats

194
00:08:50,051 --> 00:08:51,950
and provide them
with a safe, stable,

195
00:08:51,952 --> 00:08:53,619
loving family
environment.

196
00:08:53,621 --> 00:08:55,621
Oh, that sounds wonderful.

197
00:08:55,623 --> 00:08:58,891
Does one have to be a gorilla
to apply for admittance?

198
00:08:58,893 --> 00:09:00,176
I'm afraid so.

199
00:09:00,178 --> 00:09:02,144
Story of my life.

200
00:09:02,146 --> 00:09:03,312
When I was little,
I always wanted

201
00:09:03,314 --> 00:09:04,513
to play with the gorillas.

202
00:09:04,515 --> 00:09:07,399
I even made up my own
imaginary gorilla friend.

203
00:09:07,401 --> 00:09:08,767
Remember Magilla, Mom?

204
00:09:08,769 --> 00:09:11,470
Hmm, yeah,
but he wasn't imaginary.

205
00:09:11,472 --> 00:09:13,439
What?

206
00:09:13,441 --> 00:09:15,140
Walden, Magilla lived
with us

207
00:09:15,142 --> 00:09:17,359
for the first four years
of your life.

208
00:09:18,195 --> 00:09:19,778
He was real?

209
00:09:21,114 --> 00:09:22,198
Yeah.

210
00:09:22,200 --> 00:09:23,649
Do you want
to see some pictures?

211
00:09:23,651 --> 00:09:27,819
Wait, w-w-wait,
Magilla was real?

212
00:09:27,821 --> 00:09:29,255
Very much so.

213
00:09:29,257 --> 00:09:31,373
Wait, you actually had
a gorilla living with you?

214
00:09:31,375 --> 00:09:34,510
Yep, I was doing experiments
to see if gorillas could learn

215
00:09:34,512 --> 00:09:36,045
as fast as human children, so

216
00:09:36,047 --> 00:09:38,597
I raised Magilla and Walden
together from birth.

217
00:09:38,599 --> 00:09:40,633
Wow.

218
00:09:40,635 --> 00:09:44,053
All we had was a schnauzer
and an Argentinean tennis pro.

219
00:09:45,906 --> 00:09:49,058
Uncle Javier.

220
00:09:49,976 --> 00:09:52,444
The tennis pro,
not the schnauzer.

221
00:09:52,446 --> 00:09:56,848
Hold on a second,
I was raised with a gorilla?

222
00:09:56,850 --> 00:09:59,485
Oh, well, just until
you started preschool.

223
00:09:59,487 --> 00:10:02,988
Now, look, here's you and
Magilla together in your crib.

224
00:10:07,093 --> 00:10:08,327
And here's

225
00:10:08,329 --> 00:10:10,779
the two of you
at your first birthday.

226
00:10:11,831 --> 00:10:13,732
Wait a minute,

227
00:10:13,734 --> 00:10:16,535
is that how I learned
sign language?

228
00:10:16,537 --> 00:10:18,837
I'm sorry, I don't have
any bananas.

229
00:10:18,839 --> 00:10:20,706
Look, there's
the two of you

230
00:10:20,708 --> 00:10:23,192
on the playground.

231
00:10:23,194 --> 00:10:24,476
Oh, your first
Halloween.

232
00:10:25,312 --> 00:10:27,329
You went as a gorilla,

233
00:10:27,331 --> 00:10:28,764
and Magilla went as a ghost.

234
00:10:31,785 --> 00:10:33,752
Whoa, whoa.

235
00:10:33,754 --> 00:10:36,405
Yeah, okay. Yeah, it's
starting to come back to me.

236
00:10:36,407 --> 00:10:37,656
Like, riding
tricycles together,

237
00:10:37,658 --> 00:10:39,891
and running...
running around the house.

238
00:10:39,893 --> 00:10:42,444
Or playing hide in the closet.

239
00:10:42,446 --> 00:10:45,331
Wait. Why were we always
hiding in the closet?

240
00:10:45,333 --> 00:10:48,200
Well, the Homeowners Association
didn't allow cats or dogs.

241
00:10:48,202 --> 00:10:50,452
What would they have said
about a gorilla?

242
00:10:50,454 --> 00:10:52,454
Yeah. I remember.

243
00:10:52,456 --> 00:10:54,373
You told me he was my brother.

244
00:10:54,375 --> 00:10:56,709
Well, in a sense, he was.

245
00:10:56,711 --> 00:10:58,877
And then one day, he was gone.

246
00:10:58,879 --> 00:11:00,912
Yeah.

247
00:11:00,914 --> 00:11:03,015
You said
he got sent back to the jungle.

248
00:11:03,017 --> 00:11:04,750
Well, sweetheart,
we didn't have any choice.

249
00:11:04,752 --> 00:11:06,468
He was getting too big.
He, uh...

250
00:11:06,470 --> 00:11:08,754
He tried
to kill a Jehovah's Witness.

251
00:11:10,657 --> 00:11:13,091
Now, Now, to be fair,
who among us hasn't...

252
00:11:13,093 --> 00:11:14,360
Not now, Alan.

253
00:11:16,095 --> 00:11:18,030
This is really starting
to freak me out.

254
00:11:18,032 --> 00:11:19,198
Well, sweetie,
I-I don't understand

255
00:11:19,200 --> 00:11:21,533
why you're making such
a big deal out of this.

256
00:11:21,535 --> 00:11:23,452
You're kidding, right?

257
00:11:23,454 --> 00:11:26,789
I-I just discovered
